ion":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Aileen, John Patrick, Siobhan, Liam, Brigid, Donovan, Eamon, Parnell, Aidan, Clancy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallaigh</b>, or, in some areas, <b>Mac Ceallaigh</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Ceallach</i>’, an ancient Irish personal name, originally a byname meaning ‘bright-headed’, later understood as ‘frequenting churches’ (Irish <i>ceall</i>). There are several early Irish saints who bore this name. <i>Kelly</i> is now the most common of all surnames in Ireland.","Scottish: habitational name from either the lands of Kelly, near Arbroath (Angus), Kellie in Carnbee (Fife), or Kelly in Methlick (Aberdeenshire). Each of these placenames is from Pictish <i>celli</i> or Gaelic <i>coille</i> ‘wood’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-in</i>. Alternatively, from the lands of Kelloe in the barony of Hume (Berwickshire), whose name is of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Kelley","meanings":["Irish (Offaly) and English: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kilkelly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Bridie.","Irish (Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Ceallaigh</b> ‘son of the devotee of (Saint) Ceallach’ (see   Kelly  )."]},{"name":"Killeen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donovan, Kieran, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cillín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cillín</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Ceallach</i> (see   Kelly  ). The name was borne by various early Irish saints, including the leader of a 7th-century mission to Franconia and Thuringia, hence the popularity of the personal name   Kilian   in medieval central Europe."]},{"name":"Kellis","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name. Compare   Kellison  .","Greek: descriptive nickname for a bald man, from <i>kelis</i> ‘bald’, a word of Turkish origin (from <i>kel</i> ‘bald’).","History: As a surname of Scottish origin, this has been established in NC since the 18th century."]},{"name":"Kellie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kellison","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":36,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When John Kelly was born in 1346, in Cornwall, England, his father, John de Kelly, was 53 and his mother, Isabella Graham, was 30. He married Margaret Haskins. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1410, in England, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1346–1410":"1346–1410","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1348–1420":"1348–1420","1362–1420":"1362–1420","1293–1350":"1293–1350","1317–Female":"1317–Surnud","5 March 1350":"5. märts 1350","before 1330":"enne 1330","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1293":"1293","1348":"1348","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1317":"1317","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1346–1410":"1346–1410","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1348–1420":"1348–1420","1362–1420":"1362–1420","1293–1350":"1293–1350","1317–Female":"1317–Kuollut","5 March 1350":"5. maaliskuuta 1350","before 1330":"ennen vuotta 1330","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1293":"1293","1348":"1348","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","142